WEBVTT

00:17.300 --> 00:18.600
I know what you're thinking.

00:18.667 --> 00:21.433
But I have this situation
totally under control.

00:21.500 --> 00:24.133
I've been packing for this
overnight science field trip

00:24.200 --> 00:25.867
since, like, last year.

00:28.934 --> 00:31.467
Am I insane? I can't pack that.

00:31.533 --> 00:33.266
I might as well pack
the pink ducky pajamas.

00:33.333 --> 00:34.433
[QUACKING]

00:34.500 --> 00:36.600
-Sorry, Mr. Snuggles.
-[OINKS]

00:36.667 --> 00:39.133
I'd never live it down
if I brought you.

00:39.200 --> 00:40.800
Here's the low-down on our trip.

00:40.867 --> 00:44.567
Downside. Bugs, snakes,
and my science teacher, Mr. Pettus.

00:45.033 --> 00:47.433
[CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING]

00:47.500 --> 00:51.066
Upside, 48 hours
in the woods, parentless.

00:51.133 --> 00:52.834
Just me, Miranda, and Gordo.

00:52.900 --> 00:55.500
It's like <i>Survivor,</i>
but for school credit.

00:56.300 --> 00:58.400
[THEME SONG PLAYING]

01:38.667 --> 01:40.066
[PHONE RINGING]

01:40.900 --> 01:42.433
Who calls during breakfast?

01:44.066 --> 01:45.200
Hello?

01:45.266 --> 01:48.033
Okay, let's go over this
one more time.

01:48.100 --> 01:49.900
-Flashlight?
-BOTH: Check.

01:49.967 --> 01:51.400
-Non-dorky pajamas.
-BOTH: Check.

01:51.467 --> 01:54.633
Mom wants to know if you have
batteries for your flashlight.

01:54.700 --> 01:56.533
Mom, Matt's on the phone.

01:58.300 --> 02:01.667
What are you doing?
Respect your sister's privacy.

02:01.734 --> 02:03.667
Honey, do you have batteries
for that flashlight?

02:03.734 --> 02:05.800
Mom, I'm talking to my friends!

02:05.867 --> 02:07.467
I know that. I'm sorry.

02:07.533 --> 02:10.633
Hey, you guys.
Hey, Gordo. Hey, Miranda.

02:10.700 --> 02:11.900
BOTH: Hi, Mrs. McGuire.

02:11.967 --> 02:15.533
You guys are gonna have the best time
camping out, staying up all night,

02:15.600 --> 02:17.700
telling ghost stories.
You know, I remember...

02:17.767 --> 02:20.433
Okay, Mom, there wasn't enough
clean underwear for me to pack.

02:20.500 --> 02:22.233
Oh, my! Bye, guys!

02:23.533 --> 02:24.834
Brilliant ruse.

02:24.900 --> 02:27.033
Have you guys gotten "The Talk" yet?

02:27.100 --> 02:28.834
You mean
the "Stick With Your Buddy" talk?

02:28.900 --> 02:30.667
No, but I'm sure it's coming.

02:30.767 --> 02:32.066
I'll see you guys on the bus.

02:32.133 --> 02:33.734
If I don't get lost first.

02:33.800 --> 02:35.100
[ALL LAUGH]

02:36.934 --> 02:39.533
Mom, I'm old enough to pack by myself.

02:39.600 --> 02:41.100
Plus, it's only overnight.

02:41.166 --> 02:43.967
I know, but it's not like you're going
overnight to Miranda's house.

02:44.033 --> 02:46.300
You know, I can't just swing by
if you forget something.

02:46.367 --> 02:48.400
I mean, you're taking
this big step into

02:48.467 --> 02:51.133
this whole new world
and I just wanna make sure that

02:51.200 --> 02:53.567
you're fully prepared
before I let you go. [VOICE CRACKS]

02:54.800 --> 02:57.367
Now, I want you to
listen to your chaperone

02:57.433 --> 03:00.300
and stick with your buddy.

03:01.133 --> 03:02.734
Disappear once in a mall
when you're six

03:02.800 --> 03:04.266
-and you're branded for life.
-[CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING]

03:04.333 --> 03:05.800
Why can't I go camping?

03:05.867 --> 03:07.467
We'll camp this weekend with your mom.

03:08.800 --> 03:11.266
-In the house.
-[CHUCKLES]

03:11.333 --> 03:12.967
But it's not the same.

03:13.033 --> 03:16.400
I mean, you won't even let me light
a campfire in the living room.

03:16.467 --> 03:18.266
Oh, I know, he's such a wet blanket.

03:20.834 --> 03:24.100
Honey, you don't have
any toilet paper in here.

03:24.166 --> 03:27.033
Mom, it doesn't say to pack
any toilet paper on the list.

03:27.100 --> 03:30.200
Well, you can't go to the woods
without toilet paper.

03:33.467 --> 03:35.800
If humiliating me
were an Olympic event,

03:35.900 --> 03:37.734
my mother would take home the gold.

03:37.800 --> 03:39.834
[BELL RINGS]

03:43.667 --> 03:45.433
[CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING]

03:48.467 --> 03:49.600
[CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING]

03:50.400 --> 03:52.266
Hey, Lizzie. We were talking
and wanted to know

03:52.333 --> 03:54.900
if you remembered
to pack Mr. Snuggles.

03:55.000 --> 03:56.100
[OINKS]

03:56.200 --> 03:57.467
Mr. Snuggles?

03:57.533 --> 04:01.066
You know, your fuzzy little piggy
that you can't sleep without.

04:01.166 --> 04:02.734
One time at a sleepover,

04:02.800 --> 04:04.233
Lizzie forgot to pack Mr. Snuggles

04:04.300 --> 04:06.800
and her mommy had to come
and drop him off.

04:07.300 --> 04:10.200
Oh, and you had
those great pajamas, too.

04:10.233 --> 04:12.200
What were they, pink puppies?

04:12.266 --> 04:14.533
-They were ducks.
-[QUACKING]

04:14.600 --> 04:15.734
Not puppies.

04:15.800 --> 04:16.800
Whatever.

04:16.867 --> 04:19.734
Did your mommy remember to pack
your pink ducky pajamas?

04:19.800 --> 04:22.133
Or has she stopped
shopping at Dorks "R" Us?

04:22.200 --> 04:24.600
So, Kate, besides an F in Science,

04:24.667 --> 04:27.000
what else do you expect
to find in the woods today?

04:27.500 --> 04:30.767
To tell you that, I'd have
to talk to you, which I don't.

04:33.333 --> 04:35.300
I wonder if Spielberg
started this way.

04:35.367 --> 04:37.266
Thanks, Gordo.

04:37.333 --> 04:38.934
What about me? I helped.

04:39.500 --> 04:41.667
Yeah, Miranda, you helped her.

04:41.734 --> 04:43.767
"No, they were pink duckies."

04:43.834 --> 04:45.767
-[SIGHS]
-I tried.

04:45.834 --> 04:48.367
Well, I'm off to record
adolescent milestones.

04:51.800 --> 04:55.266
Danny. What do you expect
to find in the woods?

04:55.333 --> 04:59.033
Something like
<i>When Wild Animals Attack. </i>

04:59.100 --> 05:00.800
[GRUNTS]

05:00.867 --> 05:03.667
Repeat after me.
"Would you like fries with that?"

05:03.734 --> 05:05.000
Huh?

05:07.133 --> 05:10.266
Ethan, that's an interesting
choice of clothing for a camping trip.

05:10.333 --> 05:11.734
Care to explain it?

05:11.800 --> 05:13.967
Get that camera out of my grill, dawg.

05:15.333 --> 05:18.433
That was almost the shortest
filmmaking career ever.

05:18.500 --> 05:20.166
Get me before Mr. Pettus comes in.

05:20.266 --> 05:21.233
Okay, Gordo.

05:21.300 --> 05:23.367
What do you expect
to find in the woods?

05:23.433 --> 05:26.166
Well, I expect to find
a lot of animals.

05:26.233 --> 05:27.433
I really like bear...

05:27.533 --> 05:28.800
Okay, kids, listen up.

05:28.867 --> 05:31.066
A final announcement
before we load up the bus.

05:31.133 --> 05:34.200
There's a small problem
with the, uh, girl's chaperone.

05:34.266 --> 05:37.100
Uh, it seems our own Mrs. Stebel
ate a little something...

05:37.166 --> 05:39.133
Well, no need to
badmouth the cafeteria.

05:39.200 --> 05:42.166
Now, don't worry,
we don't have to cancel

05:42.233 --> 05:44.133
because we found
a last-minute replacement.

05:44.200 --> 05:46.767
Ugh, I hope it's not Coach Kelly.

05:46.834 --> 05:49.400
I secretly think that
she and Mr. Booth, the janitor,

05:49.467 --> 05:50.567
are the same person.

05:50.633 --> 05:51.967
[LIZZIE GASPS] Or Mrs. Nangle.

05:52.033 --> 05:54.667
She has the weirdest teeth.
I saw her eating lunch once.

05:54.734 --> 05:55.834
Ugh, scary.

05:55.900 --> 05:58.100
Anyone you get's going to be
better than Mr. Pettus.

05:58.166 --> 06:00.433
I put a frog in his lab coat
on Monday.

06:02.633 --> 06:04.166
It's still there today.

06:04.233 --> 06:06.667
Well, let's see who
our mystery chaperone is.

06:06.734 --> 06:08.133
And here she is.

06:08.200 --> 06:10.033
A big round of applause
for the chaperone

06:10.100 --> 06:12.367
who stepped in and saved the day.

06:12.433 --> 06:14.000
Mrs. McGuire!

06:17.533 --> 06:18.567
[MOUTHING]

06:19.834 --> 06:23.266
This is not happening. This is
not happening. This is not happening.

06:23.333 --> 06:25.300
-Hey, guys.
-Hey, Mrs. McGuire.

06:25.367 --> 06:26.500
Hi, Mrs. McGuire.

06:26.567 --> 06:27.700
Not happening!

06:27.767 --> 06:28.867
Mom, what are you doing here?

06:28.934 --> 06:30.500
Were you listening?

06:30.567 --> 06:32.500
Mrs. Stebel ate in the cafeteria.

06:32.567 --> 06:34.333
Mom, I swear I won't get lost.

06:34.400 --> 06:36.567
Well, of course
you won't get lost, honey

06:36.633 --> 06:38.700
'cause I'm gonna be your buddy.

06:38.800 --> 06:40.533
And don't worry, I won't embarrass you

06:40.600 --> 06:42.367
'cause remember, I'm a cool mom.

06:43.066 --> 06:44.700
McGuire's a common name.

06:44.767 --> 06:47.166
Maybe people will think
it's a coincidence.

06:47.266 --> 06:48.800
Hi, Mrs. McGuire.

06:48.867 --> 06:51.567
Did Lizzie forget to pack
Mr. Snuggles again?

06:51.633 --> 06:54.333
Mr. Snuggles wasn't invited.

06:54.400 --> 06:58.967
But I remembered to bring
enough toilet paper for everybody.

07:00.967 --> 07:04.066
Guess what?
You can die of embarrassment.

07:05.834 --> 07:07.066
Where's Mom?

07:07.133 --> 07:08.734
She's on her field trip with Lizzie.

07:08.834 --> 07:12.066
Mom's chaperoning Lizzie's field trip?

07:12.133 --> 07:15.100
-Yep.
-Lizzie's going to hate that.

07:16.567 --> 07:17.934
Cool.

07:18.033 --> 07:19.734
It's just us men tonight.

07:19.800 --> 07:22.200
Men, men, men, men,
men, men, men, men, men, men!

07:22.266 --> 07:25.333
Son, why don't we see
what Mom left us for dinner?

07:32.066 --> 07:33.166
Hmm.

07:37.600 --> 07:39.567
It's that tuna-noodle casserole

07:39.633 --> 07:43.166
she's been trying to get us to eat
for the past three weeks.

07:43.233 --> 07:46.000
Oh, man, that is just plain mean.

07:47.300 --> 07:53.467
It says to "heat at 350 degrees
for 20 minutes."

07:53.533 --> 07:55.567
I don't think heating's going to help.

07:55.633 --> 07:56.900
It's just going to make it angry.

07:57.500 --> 07:59.066
We're going to starve, aren't we?

07:59.133 --> 08:03.266
It's just going to be like that movie
where everybody starved, isn't it?

08:03.333 --> 08:04.900
We're not going to starve.

08:04.967 --> 08:07.867
-We aren't?
-No, son. We're gonna cook.

08:08.433 --> 08:10.166
[SCREAMS]

08:10.233 --> 08:12.266
We're going to starve!

08:12.333 --> 08:15.033
Aah, we're going to starve!

08:15.133 --> 08:17.367
Now, don't you worry
your spiky little head.

08:17.433 --> 08:19.066
I got it under control.

08:20.633 --> 08:23.300
[SCREAMS] We're going to starve!

08:29.166 --> 08:31.233
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

08:31.867 --> 08:34.767
The object of this afternoon's hike
is to identify and classify

08:34.834 --> 08:37.700
as many species of plants
and animals as possible.

08:37.767 --> 08:39.500
We're going to split up
into two groups.

08:39.567 --> 08:41.867
The girls will be led by Mrs. McGuire.

08:41.934 --> 08:43.934
-They will be the Tagi.
-[LOUDLY] Yeah!

08:45.266 --> 08:46.834
And the boys will be led by myself.

08:46.900 --> 08:48.467
We will be the Pagong.

08:49.100 --> 08:52.300
The group who identifies
the most species of plants and animals

08:52.367 --> 08:54.200
will not have to eat a rat for dinner.

08:58.500 --> 08:59.967
I-I-I'm kidding, of course.

09:04.900 --> 09:07.800
Must've jumped into my pocket
when we got off the bus.

09:08.667 --> 09:10.767
-Hop away, little fellow.
-[PLOPS]

09:15.000 --> 09:17.400
He must be nocturnal.

09:17.467 --> 09:20.467
Anyway, the winners
will get to relax after the hike.

09:20.533 --> 09:23.834
Uh, and the losers
will get to dig up earthworms

09:23.900 --> 09:26.066
with me for the class worm farm.

09:26.133 --> 09:27.467
Any questions?

09:28.533 --> 09:30.467
-Uh, yes, Kate.
-KATE: You don't mean

09:30.533 --> 09:32.734
worms from the ground, do you?

09:33.967 --> 09:36.567
Yes, Kate, worms from the earth.

09:36.633 --> 09:38.400
Earthworms.

09:38.900 --> 09:41.600
Can I bring a doctor's note
on Monday to excuse me from this?

09:41.700 --> 09:42.700
No.

09:42.767 --> 09:44.433
Then how do I get out of worm digging?

09:44.500 --> 09:48.200
MR. PETTUS: You identify
more plants and animals than the boys.

09:48.300 --> 09:50.266
Okay, everybody, let's go.

09:50.333 --> 09:51.867
Pagong, follow me.

09:53.133 --> 09:54.233
Here we go.

09:56.367 --> 09:58.233
Mrs. McGuire, we'd better not lose.

09:58.300 --> 10:00.600
I am so not digging for worms.

10:00.667 --> 10:03.233
Well, that means
we so need to win. [CHUCKLES]

10:04.333 --> 10:07.066
Okay, girls, who are we?

10:07.567 --> 10:09.667
You guys go, Tagi!

10:11.133 --> 10:12.433
[ALL SLUGGISHLY] Tagi.

10:12.500 --> 10:13.567
What are we gonna do?

10:14.100 --> 10:15.433
And you guys go, win!

10:16.266 --> 10:18.100
[ALL SLUGGISHLY] Win.

10:18.867 --> 10:20.200
Okay, then.

10:26.166 --> 10:29.000
Tonight on <i>LizzieVision. </i>
<i>"When Good Moms Go Bad."</i>

10:47.166 --> 10:49.433
I was right. It is
a Yellow-Bellied Sapsucker.

10:49.500 --> 10:51.967
Excellent job. High-five, girlfriend!

10:52.567 --> 10:55.100
My Mom just high-fived my best friend.

10:55.200 --> 10:58.200
And the worst part is
she actually thinks she's being cool.

10:59.333 --> 11:01.667
Okay, "Yellow-Bellied Sapsucker.

11:01.734 --> 11:04.834
Found in woodlands.
Drills holes in bark to get..."

11:04.900 --> 11:06.600
-"Salt?"
-Got it.

11:06.667 --> 11:08.800
-"Half a dozen oranges?"
-Got it.

11:08.900 --> 11:10.633
"One whole duck."

11:12.900 --> 11:14.200
A whole duck.

11:15.200 --> 11:16.867
-Huh.
-No got it.

11:16.934 --> 11:19.734
We got hamburger and fudgsicles.

11:19.800 --> 11:22.567
You know, duck isn't
entirely necessary for duck l'orange.

11:22.633 --> 11:23.900
We'll improvise.

11:23.967 --> 11:26.533
The best chefs in the world
always think on their feet.

11:29.767 --> 11:31.767
I got a bad feeling about this.

11:31.834 --> 11:32.867
Me, too.

11:32.934 --> 11:35.867
And that is the story of
the Yellow-Bellied Sapsucker.

11:35.934 --> 11:38.200
[SNORING]

11:40.800 --> 11:43.033
Come on, girls! Get up.

11:47.667 --> 11:49.100
Oh, it's really quiet.

11:53.834 --> 11:55.734
It is too quiet.

12:01.700 --> 12:02.967
Do you see something?

12:03.967 --> 12:04.967
No.

12:06.133 --> 12:07.467
Is anybody there?

12:10.200 --> 12:11.600
-Pagong! Pagong!
-[GIRLS SCREAMING]

12:33.500 --> 12:35.500
Ugh! How could you do that?

12:35.600 --> 12:38.467
I was just getting in touch with
my hunter-warrior instincts.

12:38.533 --> 12:40.467
-Gordo!
-Survival of the fittest?

12:40.533 --> 12:42.266
-Gordo!
-It was Ethan's idea!

12:42.767 --> 12:43.800
[SCREAMS]

12:46.633 --> 12:48.400
Don't leave your buddy!

12:51.934 --> 12:53.300
LIZZIE: That was so unfair!

12:53.367 --> 12:54.967
How could we have identified anything?

12:55.033 --> 12:56.967
Our guidebooks were soaked.

12:57.033 --> 12:59.367
Mr. Pettus should have
disqualified them.

12:59.433 --> 13:02.967
That was the grossest thing
I have ever done.

13:03.033 --> 13:05.500
I can't believe I touched a worm.

13:05.567 --> 13:07.133
A worm?

13:07.200 --> 13:09.000
Try hundreds of worms.

13:09.066 --> 13:11.233
[CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING]

13:13.333 --> 13:15.200
You know, this is all
your mother's fault.

13:15.300 --> 13:17.233
She is a terrible leader.

13:17.300 --> 13:19.300
What a waste of a manicure.

13:19.367 --> 13:21.433
It doesn't matter whose fault it is.

13:21.934 --> 13:24.500
The point is, we have to
get back at the boys.

13:24.567 --> 13:25.734
Any ideas?

13:27.633 --> 13:30.633
Earthworms in their bunks.

13:30.700 --> 13:32.834
Absolutely not, Lizzie.

13:32.900 --> 13:35.300
At 6:27 on Friday night,

13:35.367 --> 13:38.000
my mother destroyed
what was left of my life.

13:38.066 --> 13:39.200
There is no way

13:39.266 --> 13:41.967
we are putting earthworms
in the boys' bunks tonight.

13:42.000 --> 13:43.100
Forget the boys.

13:43.166 --> 13:45.433
Mom's getting earthworms
in her bunk tonight.

13:45.500 --> 13:48.100
Oh, yeah. Someone would
have to take them in there.

13:48.166 --> 13:50.433
Do we really wanna
touch the worms again?

13:51.500 --> 13:52.533
Forget it.

13:52.600 --> 13:54.533
And besides, boys like earthworms.

13:54.600 --> 13:55.900
We have to get them back

13:55.967 --> 14:00.333
and the only thing we have more
of than earthworms is toilet paper.

14:00.867 --> 14:03.300
Maybe we should
fill their bunks with toilet paper.

14:03.800 --> 14:05.166
[GASPS]

14:05.233 --> 14:07.233
Oh, that's a great idea.

14:09.200 --> 14:10.333
Huh?

14:41.266 --> 14:44.166
Maybe we shouldn't have
tried to make duck l'orange.

14:44.233 --> 14:46.667
Especially not with hamburger.

14:46.767 --> 14:49.633
You know, the tuna-noodle
casserole's sounding pretty good.

14:50.633 --> 14:52.133
That's the hunger talking.

14:54.266 --> 14:55.367
Dad,

14:55.433 --> 14:56.967
are we going to die?

15:08.500 --> 15:10.734
Okay, come on. Now, this is fun.

15:10.834 --> 15:13.166
You wouldn't be saying that
if it was your mom.

15:13.233 --> 15:16.400
My mom wouldn't lead
a midnight TP raid on the boys' tent.

15:16.934 --> 15:18.400
Okay. This is it.

15:18.467 --> 15:19.533
Mrs. McGuire,

15:19.600 --> 15:21.934
are you gonna get us
into any more trouble?

15:21.967 --> 15:24.100
Yeah, you may get in trouble.

15:24.166 --> 15:26.800
Well, stay in the tent
and let the boys have their victory.

15:26.867 --> 15:30.066
Stay in the tent and maybe
you won't get detention.

15:30.133 --> 15:33.633
Or you can follow me and TP.

15:34.867 --> 15:36.533
Here. Do your warpaint.

15:36.600 --> 15:38.900
Are you kidding me?
Stop encouraging her!

15:39.000 --> 15:40.934
Come on. If this was
anyone else's mom,

15:41.000 --> 15:42.834
you'd be having the time of your life.

15:42.900 --> 15:44.734
Exactly. But it's not.

15:44.800 --> 15:47.300
Okay, girls, we have this one chance,

15:47.367 --> 15:50.033
this one moment
to get back at the boys.

15:51.066 --> 15:54.300
Don't let your digging
for earthworms be in vain.

15:54.934 --> 15:55.967
Who are we?

15:56.066 --> 15:57.333
ALL: Tagi!

15:57.400 --> 15:58.400
What are we gonna do?

15:58.467 --> 15:59.567
ALL: Win!

16:00.133 --> 16:01.333
Let's do this.

16:47.900 --> 16:49.734
You guys, go! Get out!

16:49.834 --> 16:51.233
Go! Run back to the tent.

16:52.066 --> 16:53.867
[CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING]

16:57.100 --> 16:58.467
[BOYS SNORING]

17:12.934 --> 17:13.967
Ugh.

17:15.467 --> 17:16.467
Oh.

17:16.567 --> 17:17.767
Mrs. McGuire?

17:20.734 --> 17:23.200
No!

17:27.700 --> 17:30.200
[BOYS LAUGHING]

17:35.433 --> 17:36.667
Tagi.

17:43.600 --> 17:45.166
MATT: Pizza's good.

17:45.233 --> 17:47.133
Got here quick too, huh?

17:47.233 --> 17:50.500
Dad, we've got to hang out more often.

17:52.266 --> 17:54.934
Hang on, what was with
the toilet paper that you brought?

17:55.000 --> 17:57.233
Listen, you know what, you're just
being so unfair. I can't even believe

17:57.300 --> 17:58.700
-I'm having this conversation here.
-I'm being unfair?

17:58.800 --> 18:00.200
I'm being unfair? You...

18:00.266 --> 18:02.233
Detention for a year
is the odds-on favorite.

18:02.300 --> 18:03.700
Ugh, you're not helping.

18:03.767 --> 18:05.867
This whole thing was your stupid idea.

18:06.266 --> 18:07.734
Now your mom's going to tell

18:07.800 --> 18:09.834
and we're all going to be in trouble.
Thanks, Lizzie.

18:09.900 --> 18:11.433
Well, you did it, too.

18:11.500 --> 18:13.100
[SCOFFS] Whatever.

18:14.066 --> 18:15.900
She's right. We're so busted.

18:16.000 --> 18:17.033
It happens.

18:17.100 --> 18:19.033
No. I cannot get detention.

18:19.100 --> 18:21.633
People like me
don't do well in detention.

18:21.700 --> 18:22.867
I'll never survive.

18:22.934 --> 18:24.367
It'll go on my permanent record.

18:24.433 --> 18:25.834
I won't be able to get into college

18:25.900 --> 18:28.834
and I'll end up dipping cones
at the local Dairy Freeze.

18:28.900 --> 18:30.233
I like those cones.

18:32.300 --> 18:33.500
I'll be going now.

18:34.266 --> 18:36.333
That's not how a chaperone should act.

18:41.033 --> 18:42.967
Okay, kids. Listen up.

18:43.033 --> 18:46.567
Mrs. McGuire, are we going to
have detention forever?

18:46.633 --> 18:48.300
Girls,

18:48.367 --> 18:50.000
when you're an adult, you learn that

18:50.066 --> 18:52.967
all of your actions have consequences.

18:53.467 --> 18:54.533
Knew it.

18:55.700 --> 18:57.867
And you have to live with
those consequences, good or bad.

18:58.633 --> 18:59.667
It's gonna be bad.

19:00.800 --> 19:02.633
It's gonna be real bad.

19:02.700 --> 19:04.834
But one thing about being a kid

19:04.900 --> 19:08.700
is that you have parents
who can sometimes bail you out.

19:11.066 --> 19:13.000
I told Mr. Pettus I acted alone.

19:18.200 --> 19:19.500
I took the rap.

19:21.934 --> 19:25.934
Okay, just when you're ready
to trade her in for a new model,

19:26.000 --> 19:27.600
your Mom does something cool

19:27.700 --> 19:29.166
and you realize

19:29.233 --> 19:32.367
she's pretty much the coolest mom
in the whole world.

19:33.333 --> 19:34.800
Mom.

19:34.867 --> 19:38.000
Oh. What have I done to annoy you now?

19:38.800 --> 19:41.200
Okay, I guess I've been
a little hard on you.

19:41.300 --> 19:42.467
Yeah.

19:42.533 --> 19:43.667
Then I'm sorry

19:43.734 --> 19:46.533
because I'm really glad that
you could come along on this trip.

19:47.100 --> 19:49.300
-You are?
-Yeah.

19:49.367 --> 19:51.033
Honey, I know having your mom along

19:51.133 --> 19:54.467
wasn't exactly what you had
in mind for this weekend.

19:54.533 --> 19:56.667
Well, not exactly.

19:57.500 --> 20:00.734
But I think everyone
really kind of wishes that

20:00.800 --> 20:02.333
you were their mom right now.

20:05.500 --> 20:07.100
And I'm really glad that you're mine.

20:11.033 --> 20:12.033
Ooh.

20:12.567 --> 20:14.500
High-fives are always
really dorky, though.

20:14.600 --> 20:15.767
Oh, thank you.

20:17.500 --> 20:19.767
-Who are we?
-GIRLS: Tagi!

20:19.834 --> 20:22.033
-What are we gonna do?
-GIRLS: Win!

20:22.100 --> 20:24.467
Okay, let's get on the bus.

20:26.500 --> 20:27.533
Kate.

20:28.400 --> 20:30.066
I think you owe me an apology.

20:30.133 --> 20:32.734
-I don't owe you an apology.
-You're right.

20:32.800 --> 20:34.500
You owe my mom an apology.

20:34.934 --> 20:37.433
You know, without my mom,
this trip would have been canceled.

20:37.500 --> 20:39.633
She dug worms with us
and she took the blame

20:39.700 --> 20:41.066
for something we all did.

20:41.700 --> 20:43.000
Now, you owe her an apology.

20:43.066 --> 20:44.767
You're insane.

20:44.834 --> 20:47.200
Whatever happened to the Kate
I used to be friends with?

20:47.600 --> 20:49.734
The Kate I used to
have sleepovers with?

20:49.834 --> 20:52.600
Or the Kate that I have pictures of
with her favorite teddy bear?

20:53.433 --> 20:56.667
Um, Mr. Stewart Wugglesby?

20:59.700 --> 21:01.033
So, where's your mom?

21:04.800 --> 21:06.500
Um, Mrs. McGuire?

21:06.567 --> 21:07.934
[BELL RINGS]

21:09.266 --> 21:10.367
Hi, Lizzie.

21:10.834 --> 21:11.867
Hey!

21:13.266 --> 21:14.567
Way to go!

21:18.133 --> 21:19.667
The next Monday at school,

21:19.734 --> 21:22.333
my mom was pronounced
Coolest Mom Ever,

21:22.400 --> 21:24.967
of all time, in the history
of the universe.

21:25.033 --> 21:26.967
She could always lead
next month's TP raid

21:27.033 --> 21:28.967
during the museum field trip.

21:29.000 --> 21:31.400
Lizzie, is your mom chaperoning that?

21:31.467 --> 21:33.133
I don't think she'll be
chaperoning for a while.

21:33.200 --> 21:34.200
[ALL LAUGH]

21:34.500 --> 21:36.800
Sometimes, you do get
the best of both worlds.

21:37.533 --> 21:41.133
A cool mom and a parent
banned from all school field trips.

21:45.266 --> 21:47.233
-MAN: Mark.
-Without my mom...

21:47.300 --> 21:48.834
[BOTH LAUGH]

21:48.900 --> 21:49.900
I can do this. I can do this.

21:55.400 --> 21:57.633
[SCREAMS] Ew!

21:57.700 --> 21:59.667
-[GIRLS LAUGHING]
-That was not funny!

22:03.333 --> 22:04.867
[THEME MUSIC PLAYING]
